It's hard to say whether <hymn>Our Prayer to Thee (#1048)</hymn> would have become as popular as it currently is had President Nelson not passed away recently. We'll never know. But it lost its spot as the top hymn in this batch during Christmastime when <hymn>Go Tell It on the Mountain (#1208)</hymn> took the lead.



## What hymns are most popular each week?

This plot shows how popular each hymn is each week. Out of all the fifth batch hymns sing in a given week, what percentage of them were <hymn>Our Prayer to Thee (#1048)</hymn>, for example?


::: {.cell .column-page}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=1248}
:::
:::


Since the data is still so sparse, it's important to to put too much weight into the percentages. But it is clear that <hymn>Our Prayer to Thee (#1048)</hymn> is the lion's share of fifth batch hymns, at least for the first few weeks. Something we're seeing though is that two other hymns, <hymn>Thou Gracious Lord, Whose Mercy Lends (#1042)</hymn> and <hymn>Help Us Remember (#1043)</hymn> were more common after about a month of their release, with roughly a quarter to a third of wards that have sung fifth-batch hymns singing them. In the Christmas season, <hymn>Go Tell It on the Mountain (#1208) saw a huge spike, as did <hymn>Little Baby in a Manger (#1209)</hymn>. 


## When during meetings are these hymns sung?

We can also see when during sacrament meetings these hymns have been sung. Data sparsity makes this a pretty unreliable table though. We'll have to wait a few more weeks or months to really see some more meaningful trends. The only one that is somewhat trustworthy is, you guessed it, <hymn>Our Prayer to Thee (#1048)</hymn>.


